# Knowledge-system settings for this project.
# Written by /init-ai-workspace. Safe to edit by hand. Commit this file.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# archive — what /end-session keeps of each conversation.
#
# When you and Claude decide something, the reason lives in the conversation.
# A note saying "we chose Postgres" is only trustworthy if you can go back and
# read WHY. So /end-session can save the conversation into this repo and have
# your notes point at it.
#
# The catch: a conversation contains whatever was said in it. Client names,
# unreleased plans, personal details, a password someone pasted in. Saving it
# is useful. PUBLISHING it usually isn't. These modes are that choice.
#
#   local   Save the conversation to ai/session/raw/, never commit it.
#           It stays on this computer. Other people who clone this repo won't
#           get it, so your notes' sources won't open for them.
#           <-- DEFAULT. Right for almost everyone, and always right if unsure.
#
#   shared  Save it AND commit it, so teammates (and anyone who can read this
#           repo) get it too. Only for PRIVATE repos, and only if you accept
#           that everything said in the session ships with the code.
#           NEVER use this on a public repo.
#
#   off     Don't save conversations at all. Safest. The cost: a decision's
#           "why" has no source anyone can open, so `okf --check` will flag
#           those notes. Choose this if the work is confidential.
#
# Not sure? Leave it as `local`. You can change it any time; it only affects
# sessions from that point on.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
archive = local

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Two things this setting does NOT do, so you aren't surprised:
#
# 1. The raw .jsonl transcript is NEVER committed, in any mode. It contains the
#    output of every command Claude ran — which can include environment
#    variables, file contents, and API keys printed by ordinary tools. The
#    tooling refuses to write it anywhere that isn't gitignored.
#
# 2. The secret scan is not a safety net. It finds keys with a recognisable
#    shape (ghp_..., sk-ant-..., AKIA...). It CANNOT find passwords, database
#    connection strings, personal data, or internal hostnames — those look like
#    ordinary text. "0 hits" means "nothing obvious", never "safe to publish".
#
# If a secret ever does get committed: deleting the file is not enough. Git
# keeps it in history, and anyone who cloned or forked already has it. Rotate
# the credential — that is the only real fix.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
